msContents.summary: This manuscript is a calligraphic copy of Veterinariae medicinae libri ii by Jean Ruel, physician of Francis I. Ruel translated Greek veterinary texts by authors such as Apsyrtus, Hierocles, Pelagonius, Theomnest, Eumelus, Anatolius, and Hippocrates into Latin and compiled them into a single work. The manuscript was likely copied from the edition printed in 1530, even though it is divided into three books rather than two as in the printed edition. It is quite a deluxe production, written in humanistic cursive script on parchment with one or more initials with botanical decorations on nearly every page. An inscription in Dutch by Joannes Helewaert, possibly the scribe, is written inside the back cover.

supportDesc.extent: 158; 335 x 225 mm bound to 355 x 243 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Pagination in ink, upper outer corners, 1-227, 224-274

layoutDesc.layout: One column of forty-one lines; frame-ruled in red ink with double bounding lines; blank leaves before and after text ruled for two columns; written area: 235 x 115 mm

decoDesc.decoNote: Illuminated initials, from two to five lines, the larger ones mostly on gold wash ground, with botanical illustrations, and the smaller ones in gold on colored grounds; large twelve- or thirteen-line initials at the three book divisions (pages 1, 155, 240); chapter titles and author names in red ink

binding.p: Original binding, blind-stamped calf over wooden boards
